Loading Safegraph Data

NOTE: Per your data sharing agreement, do not save raw Safegraph data outside the P Drive Restricted Data Library. You can create a folder for yourself in Restricted Data Library/Safegraph/covid19analysis and store things there. If you have any questions about this, please contact the teaching team.

In the code below, we load the weekly pattern data, subset to San Jose, and append latitude, longitude, and NAICS code. See https://docs.safegraph.com/docs/weekly-patterns for explanation of new 4/5 release.

#Load the SafeGraph places dataset.
poi_ca <- readRDS(poi_url)

#Load the SafeGraph patterns dataset.
sg <- readRDS(patterns_W200405)

#Load the SafeGraph home panel summary.
hps <- readRDS(home_panel_W200405)

#Subset to SJ
sg_sj <- 
  sg %>% 
  filter(city == "San Jose") %>% 
  left_join(
    poi_ca %>% 
      dplyr::select(
        safegraph_place_id,
        latitude,
        longitude,
        top_category,
        sub_category
      ),
    by = "safegraph_place_id"
  )

Filter to parks, NAICS 712190:

sg_sj_parks <- 
  sg_sj %>% 
  filter(naics_code == 712190) %>% 
  arrange(desc(raw_visit_counts))

#Look at top visited, raw counts.
head(sg_sj_parks[,c("location_name", "raw_visit_counts")])

Safegraph Normalization

Use the normalization script. Keep in mind that the multiplier changes based on the Safegraph dataset time period, so you should run this with each pair of main and home panel weekly data.

One important note when using the 4/5 weekly data and onwards, which is described in the schema online: Previously origin_raw_visitor_counts was constrained to a minimum of 5, which meant they werent telling us the origin block groups that had < 5 visitors. Now, with the 4/5 release and onwards, they are showing origin block groups with at least 2 visitors, which is good for us. But for 2-4 visitors, they list origin_raw_visitor_counts as 4. That means that for these origin block groups, the number produce through the normalization may be up to twice as much as Safegraph actually has observed (this is before we add the uncertainties in their small sample size, and the uncertainties of our specific normalization approach). We havent accounted for this yet, so just note that the we may be overestimating the number of recorded visits.

#Store monthly visits/visitors separately so that we don't lose the data.
sg_sj_parks$month_raw_visit_counts <- sg_sj_parks$raw_visit_counts
sg_sj_parks$month_raw_visitor_counts <- sg_sj_parks$raw_visitor_counts

#The normBG functions is a complex-form of normalizing, which takes into account all visitors and their home blockgroups, an multiplies each visitor by a suitable factor corresponding to the population of his/her home block group.
#The new column visit_counts now stores the normalized visit values for the whole month.
sg_sj_parks_norm <- normBG(sg_sj_parks, hps)

#Duplicate the visit_counts data, just to be safe.
sg_sj_parks_norm$month_visit_counts <- sg_sj_parks_norm$visit_counts

Group by and summarize back to destination points

sg_sj_parks_sum <-
  sg_sj_parks_norm %>% 
  group_by(safegraph_place_id) %>% 
  summarize(
    visitor_counts = sum(origin_visitor_counts, na.rm=T),
    visit_counts = sum(visit_counts, na.rm=T)
  ) %>% 
  left_join(sg_sj_parks, by = "safegraph_place_id")

Plot the number of visits

Finally, we visualize the visit counts. We use leaflet to do so. We employ a logarithmic color scale.

sj_boundary <-
  places("CA",cb=F,progress_bar=F) %>% 
  filter(NAME == "San Jose") %>% 
  st_transform(4326)

sg_sj_parks_sum %>% 
  # mutate(
  #   log_visit_counts = 
  #     pmax(
  #       log(visit_counts,10),
  #       0
  #     )
  # ) %>% 
  dplyr::select(
    location_name,
    street_address,
    city,
    region,
    postal_code,
    brands,
    naics_code,
    longitude,
    latitude,
    raw_visit_counts,
    visit_counts
  ) %>% 
  leaflet() %>% 
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% 
  addPolygons(
    data = sj_boundary,
    fill = F,
    color = "gray",
    weight = 1,
    label = ~NAME
  ) %>% 
  addCircles(
    lng = ~longitude,
    lat = ~latitude,
    color = "blue",
    weight = 0.25,
    radius = ~sqrt(visit_counts)*10,
    fillOpacity = 0.5,
    label = ~paste0(location_name, ": ", round(visit_counts,-1)," visits in week of 4/5/20"),
    highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
      weight = 2,
      opacity = 1
    )
  )

Strangely, the filter to San Jose city from earlier doesnt seem to filter to San Jose, but to all of Santa Clara County. To filter to SJ city limits:

sg_sj_parks_sum_actual <-

And heres how to map the visitors to one specific park, the #1 one from the previous list

top_visited_park <-
  sg_sj_parks_sum_actual %>% 
  arrange(desc(visit_counts)) %>% 
  .[1,] %>% 
  pull(location_name)

ca_blockgroups <-
  block_groups("CA",cb=F,progress_bar=F) %>% 
  st_transform(4326) %>% 
  dplyr::select(GEOID)

blue_pal <- colorQuantile(
  palette = "Blues",
  domain = 
    sg_sj_parks_norm %>% 
    filter(location_name == top_visited_park) %>% 
    filter(!is.na(visit_counts)) %>% 
    pull(visit_counts),
  n = 5
)

top_visited_park_sum <-
  sg_sj_parks_norm %>% 
  filter(location_name == top_visited_park) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(visit_counts)) %>% 
  left_join(
    ca_blockgroups,
    by = c("origin_census_block_group" = "GEOID")
  ) %>% 
  st_as_sf()

leaflet() %>% 
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% 
  addCircles(
    data = 
      sg_sj_parks_sum_actual %>% 
      filter(location_name == top_visited_park),
    lng = ~longitude,
    lat = ~latitude,
    color = "green",
    weight = 0.25,
    radius = 1000,
    fillOpacity = 0.5,
    label = ~paste0(location_name, ": ", round(visit_counts,-1)," total visits in week of 4/5/20"),
    highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
      weight = 2,
      opacity = 1
    )
  ) %>% 
  addPolygons(
    data = top_visited_park_sum,
    fillColor = ~blue_pal(visit_counts),
    color = "blue",
    weight = 1,
    opacity = 0.5,
    fillOpacity = 0.75,
    label = ~paste0(round(visit_counts,-1)," visits to ",location_name," in week of 4/5/20"),
    highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
      weight = 2,
      opacity = 0.75
    )
  ) %>% 
  addPolygons(
    data = sj_boundary,
    fill = F,
    color = "gray",
    weight = 1,
    label = ~NAME
  ) %>% 
  setView(top_visited_park_sum$longitude[1],top_visited_park_sum$latitude[1], zoom = 12)

Note that there is a recorded origin block group all the way in Sacramento (and actually one in Connecticut as well which we dont plot). These are likely best interpreted as semi-longterm visitors, or people who have recently moved to SJ but still have their device tagged to a past residence in the Safegraph dataset.

Visitors with unknown origin

Note that within top_visited_park_sum there are important other numbers.

Number of raw devices for whom we dont have an origin census block (in other words, they were the only ones from their block group that week):

top_visited_park_sum %>% 
  filter(is.na(origin_census_block_group)) %>% 
  pull(origin_raw_visitor_counts)
## [1] 44

This is actually a lower bound because of the 2-4 visitor count simplification described earlier. The upper bound would be:

top_visited_park_sum %>% 
  mutate(
    origin_raw_visitor_counts_modified = 
      ifelse(
        origin_raw_visitor_counts == 4,
        2,
        origin_raw_visitor_counts
      )
  ) %>% 
  filter(is.na(origin_census_block_group) | origin_raw_visitor_counts == 4) %>% 
  pull(origin_raw_visitor_counts_modified) %>% 
  sum()
## [1] 84

And after our normalization, the lower bound of estimated total visitors that arent mapped:

top_visited_park_sum %>% 
  filter(is.na(origin_census_block_group)) %>% 
  pull(origin_visitor_counts) %>% 
  round()
## [1] 1353

And upper bound:

top_visited_park_sum %>% 
  mutate(
    origin_visitor_counts_modified = 
      ifelse(
        origin_raw_visitor_counts == 4,
        origin_visitor_counts/2,
        origin_visitor_counts
      )
  ) %>% 
  filter(is.na(origin_census_block_group) | origin_raw_visitor_counts == 4) %>% 
  pull(origin_visitor_counts_modified) %>% 
  sum() %>% 
  round()
## [1] 2676

Note this is almost half of the total visits were estimating for this one park during this week, so this is a reminder that the recorded origins is really only a partial representative sample of the kinds of origins for real visits to that park. Dont treat the map as a literal map of origins.

The technique shown above can be used to create ranges of visit estimates for the origin block groups with 4 raw devices, and the total visits to the destinations themselves.
